.nh
.TH NBFC-LINUX 7 "June 2026" "NBFC-Linux Manual" "Miscellaneous Information Manual"

.SH GENERAL

.SS "What is NBFC-Linux?"

NBFC-Linux is a C port of the original but unmaintained C# software NBFC (NoteBook FanControl).
It allows to control the notebook's fans by accessing the embedded controller (EC) or invoking ACPI methods.
It shares the same utilities and interfaces as the original NBFC.

.SS "What is the difference between NBFC and NBFC-Linux?"

NBFC-Linux is specifically designed and optimized for the Linux ecosystem.

It also comes with features that the original NBFC does not have, such as:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Configuration rating
.RB ( "nbfc rate-config" )
.IP \(bu 2
Support for calling ACPI methods
.IP \(bu 2
Lua scripting
.IP \(bu 2
Online configuration fetching
.IP \(bu 2
Firmware fingerprinting
.IP \(bu 2
Shell autocompletion for Bash, Fish and Zsh.
.RE

.SH INSTALLATION

.SS "Where to get NBFC-Linux from?"

NBFC-Linux can be downloaded from
.IR https://github.com/nbfc-linux/nbfc-linux .

Packages are available for
.BR Ubuntu ", " "Linux Mint" ", " Debian ", " Fedora ", " OpenSuse " and " "Arch Linux" .

.SS "Which kernel modules are required?"

For accessing the embedded controller:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B ec_sys
(most preferred)
.IP \(bu 2
.B acpi_ec
(needs to be manually installed, see
.IR "https://github.com/saidsay-so/acpi_ec" ")."

.PP
The embedded controller can also be accessed through
.IR /dev/port " (without any kernel module)."
.RE

For invoking ACPI methods:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B acpi_call
(manual compilation may be required for some distributions)
.RE

.SH CONFIGURATION

.SS "Updating configurations"

To fetch the latest configuration files from the project repository, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc update
.RE

.SS "Setting a configuration"

To set a configuration, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc config --set
.I CONFIG
.RE

Where
.I CONFIG
is the base filename of a configuration (without
.BR .json " file extension)."

.SS "Testing a configuration"

When trying out configuration files, it is recommended to follow these steps:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Set the configuration using
.B sudo nbfc config --set
.I CONFIG
.IP \(bu 2
Start the service in read-only mode using
.B sudo nbfc restart --read-only
.IP \(bu 2
Let the fan spin up and down by stressing the CPU (using
.BR "stress -c 8" )
.IP \(bu 2
Check if the reported fan speed matches the real (physical) fan speed using
.B nbfc status
.IP \(bu 2
If this is the case, restart the service in write-mode using
.B sudo nbfc restart
.IP \(bu 2
Now you can change the fan speed. See
.B USAGE
.RE

.SS "Finding a suitable configuration"

.B Automatic detection
.RS
To automatically select a configuration that matches your notebook model name, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc config --set auto
.RE

If this command does not print out an error message, the service has been configured successfully.
.RE

.B Configuration rating
.RS
To get a list of configurations that are safe to execute on the current system and may work on the device, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc rate-config --all
.RE
.RE

.B Configurations with similar names
.RS
To get a list of configuration files with a name similar to the current notebook model, run:
.RS
.B nbfc config --recommend
.RE

.B WARNING:
A similar model name does not mean that the configuration can be safely used on the device.
.B It can actually be dangerous.
Please only use configurations from this output if you are absolutely sure it is appropriate for your device.
.RE

.SS "Converting an XML model configuration from the original NBFC"

If you found a configuration that was made for the original NBFC project, you can convert it using:
.RS
.B nbfc xml2json
.I INFILE.xml
.B >
.I OUTFILE.json
.RE

In order to use the configuration, it has to be copied to
.IR @DATADIR@/nbfc/configs/ .

Such configurations may be available in the
.B NBFC-Revive
project, see
.IR "https://github.com/UraniumDonut/nbfc-revive" .

.SH ADVANCED CONFIGURATION

.SS "Changing temperature sensors attached to a fan"

If a model configuration does not configure sensors for a fan, then the default will be used, which is
.BR @CPU ,
meaning all CPU-associated sensors.

You may have to change the sensors attached to a fan, e.g. setting a fan to the
.B @GPU
sensor group.

To override the default sensors, use this command:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc sensors set -f
.I FAN
.RB [ "-s"
.IR SENSOR... ]
.RB [ "-a"
.IR ALGORITHM ]
.RE

.I ALGORITHM
is one of:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B Min
(take the minimum temperature among all specified sensors)
.IP \(bu 2
.B Max
(take the maximum temperature among all specified sensors)
.IP \(bu
.B Average
(calculate the average temperature among all specified sensors; default)
.RE

.I SENSOR
may either be a:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B "temperature file"
.IP \(bu 2
.BR "sensor name" " (which will result in one or more temperature files)"
.IP \(bu 2
.BR "sensor group " ( "@CPU" ", " "@GPU" ")"
.RE

.B NOTE:
If you are writing model configuration files, use the
.B Sensors
field. It is recommended to use sensor groups, so that the configuration works on many systems regardless of the hardware.

.SS "Showing sensors attached to a fan"

To show all fans with their configured sensors, run:
.RS
.B nbfc sensors show
.RE

.SS "Finding all available sensors"

To get a list of all available sensors, run:
.RS
.B nbfc sensors list
.RE

.SH USAGE

.SS "Getting the service status"

To get information about the service, including the notebook's fans, run:
.RS
.B nbfc status
.RE

.SS "Setting the fan speed"

To set the speed of all available fans, run:
.RS
.B nbfc set -s
.I PERCENT
.RE

To set all available fans to profile based automatic control, run:
.RS
.B nbfc set -a
.RE

To apply the fan speed to only a specific fan, run:
.RS
.B nbfc set -s
.I PERCENT
.B -f
.I FAN
.RE

.B NOTE:
.I FAN
is a number starting from zero.

.SH MISCELLANEOUS

.SS "Starting NBFC-Linux automatically at boot time"

NBFC-Linux comes with a
.B systemd
service file.

To enable NBFC-Linux to start on boot, run:
.RS
.B sudo systemctl enable nbfc_service.service
.RE

.SS "Resetting the notebook's fans to the default behaviour"

If the model configuration file for the notebook has been written properly, then
.RS
.B sudo nbfc stop
.br
\- or \-
.br
.B sudo systemctl stop nbfc_service
.RE
should reset the notebook's fans to their default behaviour.

In 99% of cases, a reboot will also reset the embedded controller.

.SH TROUBLESHOOTING

.SS "Error: No such configuration available"

The selected config file (as referenced by
.B SelectedConfigId
in
.I /etc/nbfc/nbfc.json)
does not exist.

.SS "Error: No working implementation found for accessing the embedded controller"

Neither
.B ec_sys
nor
.B acpi_ec
kernel modules are available.
Access through
.I /dev/port
is also not possible.

.SS "Error: /sys/kernel/debug/ec/ec0/io: Invalid argument"

The
.B ec_sys
kernel module is loaded, but
.B write_support
is disabled.

Edit
.I /etc/default/grub
and find the line
.B GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT 
then append
.B ec_sys.write_support=1
to it.

For example, the line should look like this:
.B GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT=\[dq]quiet kvm.enable_virt_at_load=0 ec_sys.write_support=1\[dq]

Then run
.B sudo update-grub
and reboot your system.

.SS "Error: Could not load kernel module \[dq]acpi_call\[dq]"

The
.B acpi_call
kernel module is missing. Install or build it as needed.

.SS "Error: /proc/acpi/call: AE_NOT_FOUND"

An unknown ACPI method was invoked. It usually indicates an incorrect or incompatible configuration.

.SH "NOTEBOOK FIRMWARE BACKGROUND"

.SS "What is an embedded controller (EC)?"

The embedded controller is a microcontroller within modern notebook computers. It manages system hardware functions such as fan speed, battery charging, keyboard control, LCD backlight and many more.

.SS "What is ACPI?"

The Advanced Configuration and Power Interface (ACPI) is an open industry standard for device configuration and power management. ACPI methods allow the operating system to control various hardware components.

.SH CONFIGURATION DEVELOPMENT

.SS "Safety Considerations"

Only interact with EC registers or ACPI methods you fully understand. Misuse can damage hardware.
If possible, remove the battery while creating a configuration, as accidental modification to battery registers may brick the battery permanently.

.SS "Naming configuration files"

Use the output of
.B nbfc get-model-name
as the configuration's filename.

.SS "How to analyze the firmware?"

To get a list of all registers that are accessible through the embedded controller, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc acpi-dump ec-registers
.RE

To get a list of all embedded controller registers, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc acpi-dump registers
.RE

.B WARNING:
Do not try to access those registers through
.BR ec_probe ,
as they are not exposed through the embedded controller.
Only write to registers that are listed by
.BR "sudo nbfc acpi-dump ec-registers" .

To get a list of all ACPI methods, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc acpi-dump methods
.RE

To disassemble all the ACPI firmware tables, run:
.RS
.B sudo nbfc acpi-dump dsl
.RE

.SS "How to identify fan registers?"

Search for registers named like
.BR FAN ", " RPM ", " PWM ", etc."

Examples:
.B SFAN CFAN PFAN FAN1 FSW1 FRDC FTGC RPM1 RPM2

.SS "How to identify ACPI methods?"

Search for methods named like
.BR FAN ", " RPM ", " PWM ", etc."

Examples:
.B FANG FANW GFSD SFSD SFNV FRSP STMM GFRM

.SS "Accessing the embedded controller"

For reading a register:
.RS
.B sudo ec_probe read
.I REGISTER
.RE

For reading a 16-bit register:
.RS
.B sudo ec_probe read --word
.I REGISTER
.RE

For writing to a register:
.RS
.B sudo ec_probe write
.I REGISTER
.I VALUE
.RE

For writing to a 16-bit register:
.RS
.B sudo ec_probe write --word
.I REGISTER
.I VALUE
.RE

.SS "Invoking ACPI methods"

To call an ACPI method, run:
.RS
.B sudo ec_probe acpi_call '\eMETHOD ARGS...'
.RE

.SS "Tracing embedded controller changes"

It may be useful to trace the registers of the embedded controller as the fan spins up and down.

To do so, make sure the fan is at its lowest speed, then run:

.RS
.B sudo ec_probe monitor -r
.I OUTFILE.csv
.RE

While recording, stress the CPU, run:

.RS
.B stress -c 8
.RE

When the fan reached its maximum speed, stop the
.B stress
command and wait until the fan is at its lowest speed.

You now can kill the
.B ec_probe monitor
command and inspect the
.I OUTFILE.csv
for register changes.

You can also visualize the
.I OUTFILE.csv
by running:

.RS
.B ec_probe graph
.I OUTFILE.csv
.RE

.SS "Writing complex configurations with Lua"

Sometimes a firmware must be accessed in a more complex way than the NBFC software supports.
For example, ACPI commands have to be constructed or the readings of the embedded controller have to be modified.

See
.BR nbfc_service.json (5)
for details.

.SS "Firmware Fingerprinting"

Firmware fingerprinting is especially useful if a model configuration file uses
.B ACPI WMI
methods.
Since these methods often have the same names but not the same implementation it is necessary to look for characteristics in the firmware that confirm it is the intended firmware.

See
.BR nbfc_service.json (5)
for details.

.SS "Getting Help"

See
.BR nbfc_service.json (5)
for details.

For more information, see the
.BR "Creating Model Configuration HowTo" :
.IR "https://nbfc-linux.github.io/creating-config/" .

For further assistance, visit the project at GitHub:
.IR https://github.com/nbfc-linux/nbfc-linux .

.SH CONTRIBUTING

.SS "Contributing a configuration file"

When contributing a configuration file, please also attach your firmware.
You can create an archive containing your firmware by running:

.RS
.B sudo nbfc support --create-archive
.I ARCHIVE.tar.gz
.RE

This helps the developer validate your configuration and keep the register-name database up to date.

.SS "Contributing code"

Before contributing code, please open an issue and ask if the contribution is wanted. This helps avoid frustration and prevents unnecessary work.

.SS "Uploading your firmware"

Uploading your notebook firmware helps the developer to understand existing
configuration files.

The following data will be transmitted:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
The
.B laptop manufacturer
.RI ( /sys/devices/virtual/dmi/id/sys_vendor )
.IP \(bu 2
The
.B laptop model
.RI ( /sys/devices/virtual/dmi/id/product_name )
.IP \(bu 2
The
.B ACPI DSDT
firmware table
.RI ( /sys/firmware/acpi/tables/DSDT )
.IP \(bu 2
The
.B ACPI SSDT
firmware tables
.RI ( /sys/firmware/acpi/tables/SSDT* )
.RE

.PP

The preferred method for uploading your notebook firmware is to use:

.RS
.B sudo nbfc support --upload-firmware
.RE

However, if you're paranoid, you can upload it manually using
.BR curl :

.RS
.B nbfc support --print-command
.RE

